			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Couple of ideas</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Here are a few ideas I have not really seen posted.    They may have been posted but I don't remember them.    Just a couple of related brainstorm ideas which might help with some of our issues AND be inline with whatever the current wizard definition is (not that I really know since it was never posted).<br />
<br />
-- Wizards should get a built in resist modifier which stacks with the spell and the effect.    An example of this might be  -- For each level above 30, each spell receives a bonus -1 (or -2) modifier to the spell.   So a level 70 wizard would have -40 = (-1 * (70 - 30))   added to each spell he casts.      --- This ability would be inline since somewhere long ago, wizards were said to have an advantage over other classes starting at level 30.    What SOE did was just slap a -10 modifier on cold and fire nuke big nukes and stopped there.    I think that as wizards level, they should become less resistable.<br />
<br />
<br />
-- Wizard spell casting mastery.   Since wizards are such a &quot;tight&quot; focused caster, he spends most of his time casting nukes.    I think that wizards should get a bonus modifier on mana costs for nukes.   After level 30, each spell cast cost one percent mana less (caps at 50 percent).    Look at it this way, if all we do is cast nukes and wizards are the &quot;scholarly types&quot;, then wizards should have learned to improve.<br />
<br />
-- Wizard crit modifier -- Wizards get like a 1 - 2 percent chance to land 101 - 160 percent of the spell damage as a class definition.   Why does it have to stop at 1 - 2 percent at level 10?</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
				AvgWiz -- lvl 65 Arcanist
			</div>
		<!-- / sig -->
		
		
		
	
	</td>
